patients' average anxiety score is 2.29565. the max. value is 2.9 and the min. value is 1.8. the standard error of the sampling distribution is 0.063332 , the distribution does look normal but with no value sampled within anxiety score of 2.6 and 2.8

  • The regression function is: \[\hat {y_i} = 162.88 - 1.21 {x_1}_i - 0.67 {x_2}_i -8.21 {x_3}_i + \epsilon_i\]

  • b2 = -0.67, means the decrese of a patient’s satisfaction score is 0.67 unit on average for each unit increase of illness severity when age and anxiety are fixed.

  • Question 4

  • From the regression output, the coefficient of multiple determination, namely \(R^2\), is 67.27%.

  • Question 5
  • From the regression output, the adjusted coefficient of multiple determination, namely \({R_a}^2\), is 62.1%.
  • We verify the relationship by examing the function: \(1-(1-R^2)(n-1)/(n-p)\). Here the n is the sample size 23, and the p is the number of estimated parameter here 4.

  • The result is 0.6210211 which matches the value of the adjusted coefficient of multiple determination

  • Question 6
  • Hypothesis: \(H_0: \: \beta_1 = 0 \: vs.\: H_a: \: \beta_1 \neq 0\)
  • Decision rule: p-value=0.00074 < 0.05, we reject \(H_0\).

  • Conclusion: We have sufficient evidence to conclude that the predictor of age is significant in predicting patient’s satisfaction in our model.

  • Question 7
  • Hypothesis: \(H_0: \: \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \beta_3 = 0\) vs. \(H_a\): at least two \(\beta_i\)’s are not equal.
  • Decision rule: from the output we observe the p-value= 7.482e-05 < 0.05, reject \(H_0\).

  • Conclusion: We have sufficient evidence to conclude that our linear model is appropriate. It also implied at least one of these three predictor variables is significant in explaining the response variable.
